## Breakdown
- `#include <stdio.h>`: Tells the compiler to include the Standard Input Output library (needed for `printf`).
- `int main()`: The starting point. `int` means it returns an integer.
- `{ ... }`: Curly braces define the block of code.
- `printf(...)`: A function to print text to the console.
- `return 0;`: Indicates the program finished successfully.

# Input and Output 🗣️

We use the `<stdio.h>` library for I/O.

## Output: `printf()`
Sends formatted output to the screen.
```c
printf("Age is %d", age);
```

## Input: `scanf()`
Reads formatted input from the keyboard.
```c
scanf("%d", &age);
```
> ⚠️ **Crucial:** Notice the `&` (address-of) operator before `age` in `scanf`. It tells C *where* in memory to store the input.

<!-- FULL_CODE_START
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int age;
    float height;

    printf("Enter your age: ");
    // Read an integer
    scanf("%d", &age);

    printf("Enter your height (in meters): ");
    // Read a float
    scanf("%f", &height);

    printf("\n--- Summary ---\n");
    printf("You are %d years old.\n", age);
    printf("You are %.2f meters tall.\n", height);

    return 0;
}
FULL_CODE_END -->
